eval excrescent <i>-s</i>, of <b>Haime</b>, of Norman origin, from the Old French personal name <i>Haim</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Haimo</i>, from <i>haim-</i> ‘home’), often Latinized as <i>Hamo</i>. Compare   Hammond  .","Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Raymes was born about 1206, in Aydon, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, his father, Gilbert Raymes I, was 32 and his mother, Mrs Gilbert Raymes, was -73. He married Mrs. Robert Raymes in 1229, in Aydon, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1206–":"umbes 1206–Surnud","1206–Male":"1206–Surnud","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1206":"1206","about 1206":"umbes 1206","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1280":"1280","1208":"1208","1229":"1229","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Aydon, Northumberland, England":"Aydon, Northumberland, Inglismaa, Unit